**ExpandableText** detects when its content is truncated and shows an expand/collapse button ŌĆö the button stays hidden while the content fits. It has two independent axes you choose between:

- **Truncation** ŌĆö `single_line` (clip one line with an ellipsis) or `multi_line` (clamp to a fixed number of lines)
- **Expansion mode** ŌĆö `inline` (reveal in place) or `dialog` (open a dialog with the full text)

<%= embed OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponentPreview, :default %>

For more variations, browse the [preview examples](/lookbook/inspect/OpenProject/Primer/expandable_text/default) in Lookbook.

## Choosing what to truncate

`truncate:` controls how the text is clipped ŌĆö not which way it expands.
Expansion always reveals the full text (in place or in a dialog); `single_line`
versus `multi_line` only decides how much shows while collapsed.

| `truncate:` | What you get | Reach for it when |
|-------------|--------------|-------------------|
| `single_line` (default) | A single line, cut off with an ellipsis (`ŌĆ”`) | Short labels in table cells or list rows ŌĆö permission names, statuses |
| `multi_line` | The first `lines:` rows, then clamped | Multi-line descriptions or rich-text previews |

`multi_line` takes a `lines:` count (2 or more, default 3):

<%= embed OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponentPreview, :multi_line %>

## Choosing an expansion mode

| Mode | Behaviour | Reach for it when |
|------|-----------|-------------------|
| `inline` (default) | Clicking the expander toggles the full text in place | Short content that reads fine expanded inline |
| `dialog` | The expander opens a dialog showing the full content | Long-form or formatted content better shown in a focused dialog |

In `dialog` mode the component owns the dialog and wires the expander button to
it. By default ŌĆö with no `dialog` slot ŌĆö it renders a dialog showing the full
content, which is all most callers need:

```erb
<%%= render(OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponent.new(truncate: :multi_line, lines: 2, expansion: :dialog)) do %>
  <%%= full_text %>
<%% end %>
```

<%= embed OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponentPreview, :dialog %>

Supply a `dialog` slot only when you need a custom title, header or body:

```erb
<%%= render(OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponent.new(truncate: :multi_line, lines: 2, expansion: :dialog)) do |component| %>
  <%% component.with_dialog(title: "Full description", size: :large) do |dialog| %>
    <%% dialog.with_header(variant: :large) %>
    <%% dialog.with_body_content(full_text) %>
  <%% end %>
  <%%= truncated_preview %>
<%% end %>
```

The two axes are independent. In practice two combinations cover almost every
case: **single_line + inline** (table and list labels) and **multi_line + dialog**
(long project attributes). The other combinations are valid too.

## Used in

- **Administration > Users and permissions > Permissions report** ŌĆö single-line inline (permission names in table cells)
- **Administration > Work packages > Edit workflow** ŌĆö single-line inline (status names)
- **Project attributes** ŌĆö multi-line dialog (via `AttributeComponent`, which composes `ExpandableTextComponent`)

<%= embed OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponentPreview, :in_table %>

## Best practices

**Do**

- Always place the component inside a width-constrained parent so truncation can trigger
- Pass `flex: 1` when using inside a flex container to allow the truncation wrapper to shrink
- Use the component even for text that might not truncate ŌĆö the expander stays hidden when content fits

**Don't**

- Don't set a fixed width on the component itself ŌĆö constrain the parent container
- Don't use `single_line` for multi-line content ŌĆö use `truncate: :multi_line` with a `lines:` count

## Technical notes

The component is a flex container with two children:

- **Truncation wrapper** ŌĆö `Primer::Beta::Truncate` for `single_line` (`text-overflow: ellipsis`) or `OpPrimer::VerticalTruncateComponent` for `multi_line` (`-webkit-line-clamp` driven by the inline `--op-vertical-truncate-lines` custom property)
- **Expander button** ŌĆö a `Primer::Alpha::HiddenTextExpander`, initially hidden, shown by the private `expandable-text` Stimulus controller when overflow is detected

The private `expandable-text` Stimulus controller (for `ExpandableTextComponent` only):

- Uses `ResizeObserver` (via `stimulus-use`) to reactively detect when content overflows its container
- **`single_line`:** compares `scrollWidth > clientWidth` on the `.Truncate-text` element
- **`multi_line`:** compares `scrollHeight > clientHeight` on the truncation target (works with `-webkit-line-clamp`)
- Toggles `Truncate--expanded` (`single_line`) or `op-vertical-truncate--expanded` (`multi_line`) for inline expansion
- Updates `aria-label` and `aria-expanded` for accessibility
